data.name: UnlockHandleButton.ToolTip
data.value: This will close the handle named above in the target game. Use this to run multiple instances, similar to Unlock Source engine. You will need to find the handle name with Process Explorer. (Press Ctrl+H in Process Explorer to view handles). You can unlock multiple handles at once by separating with 5 & symbols, e.g. handle1&&&&&handle2

data.name: Button_UnlockSourceEngine.ToolTip
data.value: Games made in the Source engine (most Valve games, e.g. Team Fortress 2, Left 4 Dead 2, CS:GO, etc.) will prevent you from opening multiple instances. If you target a game window and click this button, it will "unlock" it so you can open another instance.

data.name: RefCheckbox_DrawMouse.ToolTip
data.value: This program will draw a "fake" mouse cursor over the game's mouse position. Use this if the game doesn't have its own mouse cursor image and relies on the Windows mouse cursor. The fake cursor will flicker a lot because the game keeps re-drawing over it. Use this only if necessary. Enabling V-Sync in the game's options will reduce flickering significantly.

data.name: RefCheckbox_SendRawKeyboardInput.ToolTip
data.value: Forwards any raw keyboard input messages from windows to the target game. Useful if the game doesn't listen to raw input unless it is in the foreground. Use this if a game is not responding to keyboard input. Very few games use raw keyboard input, so this will likely have no effect.

data.name: RefCheckbox_SendRawMouseInput.ToolTip
data.value: Forwards any raw mouse input messages from windows to the target game. Useful if the game doesn't listen to raw input unless it is in the foreground. Use this if a game is not responding to mouse input.

data.name: RefCheckbox_Hook_GetKeyboardState.ToolTip
data.value: Some games will use GetKeyboardState to get keyboard input. Windows should in theory only report input from the message queue (ie Send normal keyboard input) but sometimes using two keyboards at once will interfere with the function. Use this hook if the game is responding to multiple keyboards.

data.name: RefCheckbox_Hook_Dinput.ToolTip
data.value: XInput is used by most games for controller input. However, XInput supports only up to 4 controllers. DirectInput supports effectively unlimited controllers. This hook translating DInput into XInput so you can use more than 4 controllers. This hook requires 'Hook XInput for gamepads' If you want to hook DInput for controller input in games that use DInput natively, see 'Hook DInput' in the Utilities tab.

data.name: RefCheckbox_UpdateAbsoluteFlagInMouseMessage.ToolTip
data.value: If checked, the absolute cursor position (ie the cursor position in UI menus) will be updated when the game processes a mouse move message. This will only have an effect if legacy input is enabled. Use this if the mouse isn't working correctly with legacy input.

data.name: RefCheckbox_Hook_MouseVisibility.ToolTip
data.value: Detects when the game wants to show/hide the mouse cursor, and adjusts the fake mouse cursor accordingly. Use this for a first person game, where the cursor should be shown in UI menus, but not in first person. This will also help if the real Windows mouse cursor keeps moving about the screen.

data.name: RefCheckbox_Hook_UseLegacyInput.ToolTip
data.value: Some games will use SetCursorPos frequently to set the cursor position to the center of its window, and GetCursorPos to calculate any mouse movement. This hook will automatically switch between delta mouse input (ie first person camera movement) and absolute mouse movement (ie in a UI menu). If you need this hook, make sure all "raw input" options are turned OFF in this page and in the games options. You will need the GetCursorPos and SetCursorPos hooks turned ON. "Send normal mouse input" is highly recommended to make menus work properly.

data.name: RefCheckbox_Hook_XInput.ToolTip
data.value: Redirects controller input to the selected controller index. This hook is required if you want to use gamepad/controller input on games that use xinput (most modern games). XInput only supports 4 controllers. Do not use a controller index higher than 4 if the game only uses XInput.

data.name: RefCheckbox_Hook_GetAsyncKeyState.ToolTip
data.value: This hook will overload GetAsyncKeyState for mouse buttons and all keyboard keys. Use this if a game is not responding to mouse buttons or keyboard keys. This will often fix issues with the shift/control/alt keys.

data.name: CheckBox_StartupHook_FindMutexHook.ToolTip
data.value: Most games will use Mutexes/Events/Semaphores to prevent multiple instances from opening. This hook will prevent any new instances from detecting if a handle with the same name already exists by appending a random number to the name. Use this to quickly launch multiple instances of a game or if the handle unlocker does not work (e.g. the game crashes immediately). You will need to find the handle names in Process Explorer (Press Ctrl+H to view handles). Separate multiple names with 5 & symbols, e.g. name1&&&&&name2

data.name: CheckBox_StartupHook_FindWindow.ToolTip
data.value: Some games will use FindWindow at launch to detect if any instances of the game are already running. Launching a game with this utility will hook FindWindow so the game cannot detect other instances. As with the other hooks, this may be detected as a false positive by an anti-virus or anti-cheat system.

data.name: CheckBox_StartupHook_UseAppdataSwitch.ToolTip
data.value:
If this is enabled, whenever a game tries to access appdata or your user folder (e.g. the Documents sub-folder), it will instead be rerouted to a unique folder for the instance. Selecting Index 1, for example, will reroute C:\Users\Username and all sub-folders to C:\Users\Username\UniversalSplitScreen\index1
This can be used to launch multiple instances if a game locks on a file. This will also allow you to use different save folders for each instance. The Goldberg Emulator saves its user ID and emulated Steam cloud in appdata, so this will also allow you to have separate Goldberg IDs for each instance.

data.name: CheckBox_StartupHook_Dinput.ToolTip
data.value: Redirects controller input within the Direct Input API. Direct Input is an old API, so it is mostly only used by old games. Direct Input supports an effectively unlimited number of controllers, so you can use more than 4 controllers.
